  "name": "Ballet: A Living Architecture",
  "description": "Ballet is architecture in motion — a 400-year tradition of codified positions, geometries of the body, and gravity-defying feats that evolved from courtly entertainment to one of humanity's most demanding art forms. This grammar maps the vocabulary (positions, steps, jumps), the canon (Swan Lake to The Rite of Spring), and the eras (court ballet to contemporary) — always asking what the body is being asked to do, and why.\n\nPUBLIC DOMAIN ILLUSTRATION REFERENCES: Edgar Degas, ballet paintings and pastels (1870s-1890s). Engravings from Raoul-Auger Feuillet's *Chorégraphie* (1700). Lithographs of Marie Taglioni and Romantic era ballerinas. Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, dance-hall paintings.",
  "grammar_type": "custom",
  "creator_name": "PlayfulProcess",
  "tags": ["ballet", "dance", "embodiment", "architecture", "classical", "european", "discipline"],
  "roots": ["western-philosophy", "embodiment"],
  "shelves": ["wonder"],
  "lineages": ["Kelty"],
  "worldview": "rationalist",
